WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:08.460 --> 00:00:16.140
I'm Norman Wildberger, and I'm excited to&nbsp;
introduce to you a new approach to arithmetic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:16.740 --> 00:00:22.440
where we incorporate some of our understanding&nbsp;
of the importance of the data structure called&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:22.440 --> 00:00:31.620
a multi-set and combine it with interesting&nbsp;
insights from 20th-century physics to form a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:31.620 --> 00:00:38.700
very viable, possible new alternative to&nbsp;
the foundational aspects of arithmetic,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:38.700 --> 00:00:43.200
which underlies most of modern mathematics.

00:00:44.160 --> 00:00:49.440
Today, I want to talk a little bit about an&nbsp;
overview of the role of arithmetic historically,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:49.440 --> 00:00:55.440
painting things with a very broad brush and just&nbsp;
giving you a sense of where we are going to go.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:56.160 --> 00:01:02.220
Arithmetic has been around, of course, for a long&nbsp;
time, initially associated perhaps with commerce,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:02.220 --> 00:01:10.860
accounting, or taxation issues in ancient&nbsp;
civilizations. While pure mathematics was&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:10.860 --> 00:01:17.160
more interested in issues having to do with&nbsp;
astronomy and related geometrical considerations,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:17.880 --> 00:01:23.820
as evidenced by Euclid's foundational text, the&nbsp;
Elements, which is very much based on geometry,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:24.360 --> 00:01:30.840
there are a few chapters dedicated to rather&nbsp;
esoteric number-theoretical considerations,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:30.840 --> 00:01:35.640
such as perfect numbers, triangular numbers,&nbsp;
primes, and factorizations. These are, of course,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:35.640 --> 00:01:40.200
very important and ultimately lead to&nbsp;
Diophantine equations and things like that,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:40.200 --> 00:01:50.040
but they are perhaps of more academic interest&nbsp;
and not firmly grounded in applied mathematics.

00:01:51.720 --> 00:02:00.960
The situation really changes when Descartes comes&nbsp;
along and introduces his Cartesian approach to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:00.960 --> 00:02:08.820
geometry, trying to clarify the definitional&nbsp;
difficulties with Euclid's geometry by firmly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:08.820 --> 00:02:15.840
establishing everything in the context of a prior&nbsp;
number system, giving us coordinates over the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:15.840 --> 00:02:21.780
plane or in higher dimensions of space.&nbsp;
We start with the underlying arithmetic,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:21.780 --> 00:02:27.840
perhaps rational numbers or something else,&nbsp;
and then we build a geometry on top of that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:27.840 --> 00:02:36.000
by essentially creating a linear space whose&nbsp;
points are given by n-tuples of our numbers.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:37.860 --> 00:02:44.760
When people did this and looked carefully, they&nbsp;
saw that various intuitive geometrical notions,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:44.760 --> 00:02:55.800
primarily length and area, often required an&nbsp;
extension or a seeming extension of our number&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:55.800 --> 00:03:01.860
system beyond the familiar rational number&nbsp;
system, even going back to the Pythagorean&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:01.860 --> 00:03:07.080
conundrum with the square root of 2 as&nbsp;
the length of a diagonal of a unit square.

00:03:08.460 --> 00:03:12.960
People started to realize that for a lot&nbsp;
of geometrical purposes, if we want to get&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:12.960 --> 00:03:19.860
something that mimics our intuition, then&nbsp;
we are forced to extend our number system&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:19.860 --> 00:03:27.060
in particular ways. This wasn't really clearly&nbsp;
encoded until the 19th century when analysts,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:27.060 --> 00:03:34.020
who were interested in trying to establish&nbsp;
function theory, also started requiring a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:34.020 --> 00:03:39.060
more careful view of what the artificial&nbsp;
underlying number system was. Ultimately,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:39.600 --> 00:03:48.000
this culminated in the current theory&nbsp;
of real numbers, around the time of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:55.860
Cauchy, Dedekind, and Weierstrass, and was&nbsp;
supported principally by Cantor's so-called&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:55.860 --> 00:04:00.720
theory of infinite sets, even though&nbsp;
that was highly debated at the time.

00:04:02.280 --> 00:04:10.080
When the 20th century came along, the difficulties&nbsp;
with the foundations of set theory had been&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:10.080 --> 00:04:14.220
circumvented a little bit by adopting a&nbsp;
philosophical point of view. From my point&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:14.220 --> 00:04:19.260
of view, it sort of delegated the foundations&nbsp;
of mathematics to the philosophers with this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:19.260 --> 00:04:28.800
axiomatic approach to set theory. This then became&nbsp;
the default starting point for arithmetic also,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:28.800 --> 00:04:37.620
and because set theory is, in my view, rather&nbsp;
a suspect subject and cannot actually be very&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:37.620 --> 00:04:47.040
clearly laid out, it meant that the foundations of&nbsp;
arithmetic were concurrently imbued with a shaky,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:47.040 --> 00:04:57.720
murky, shimmering aspect. When we go to say&nbsp;
von Neumann and his attempt to pin down even&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:57.720 --> 00:05:04.560
the basics of integer arithmetic or natural&nbsp;
numbers from a set theory point of view,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:05.340 --> 00:05:11.280
there is something a little bit forced about that,&nbsp;
I think it's fair to say, a little bit artificial.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:11.280 --> 00:05:17.040
But mathematicians have felt that there's&nbsp;
no real alternative because we've all agreed&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:17.700 --> 00:05:23.460
that set theory is the proper foundation&nbsp;
of mathematics, and therefore by default,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:23.460 --> 00:05:28.380
it's the natural place to look at for&nbsp;
the foundations of arithmetic as well.

00:05:30.660 --> 00:05:38.340
Because I'm not a believer in Zermelo-Fraenkel&nbsp;
axiomatics, I don't think axiomatics should&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:38.340 --> 00:05:44.880
play any kind of role in the foundations of&nbsp;
analysis, calculus, or even arithmetic. I'm&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:44.880 --> 00:05:52.140
looking for alternative ways, and it's my&nbsp;
firm view that the crucial data structure&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:52.740 --> 00:06:00.960
is not that of a set as far as the foundations of&nbsp;
arithmetic go, but actually the multi-set. This&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:00.960 --> 00:06:06.780
is one very clear distinction between what I'm&nbsp;
proposing and what everybody else is thinking.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:06.780 --> 00:06:13.080
For me, it's the multi-sets that provide the&nbsp;
arena where we can really have a rich arithmetic.

00:06:13.680 --> 00:06:21.120
That's one of the key starting points. We're&nbsp;
going to be developing arithmetic from very&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:21.120 --> 00:06:28.200
first principles just by thinking about multi-sets&nbsp;
and what we can do with them from a very naive&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:28.200 --> 00:06:34.500
point of view. A little bit down the road, when&nbsp;
we start thinking about making the transition&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:35.220 --> 00:06:41.940
from natural number arithmetic to integer&nbsp;
arithmetic, we're going to see that we have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:41.940 --> 00:06:51.840
to start thinking in a way that's outside&nbsp;
the usual formats of modern mathematics&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:51.840 --> 00:06:59.940
and drawing inspiration from the physicists,&nbsp;
in particular from Paul Dirac's remarkable&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:00.840 --> 00:07:08.160
discovery of the equation of the electron&nbsp;
and concurrent particle-antiparticle duality.

00:07:10.080 --> 00:07:14.280
The subject that's going to be emerging here,&nbsp;
although initially we'll be framing it in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:14.280 --> 00:07:19.620
terms of multi-sets, is ultimately going to be&nbsp;
called "box arithmetic." It will be, I think,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:19.620 --> 00:07:27.120
a very novel place and an opportunity&nbsp;
to rethink all kinds of things and to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:27.120 --> 00:07:34.200
put mathematics on a much wider and more&nbsp;
interesting foundation. We're going to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:34.200 --> 00:07:39.420
see that arithmetic actually extends far&nbsp;
beyond what we currently think it does.

00:07:40.740 --> 00:07:45.900
Another one of my main motivations is&nbsp;
to ultimately connect our subject much&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:45.900 --> 00:07:49.680
more explicitly and directly&nbsp;
with computational reality.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:50.280 --> 00:07:56.520
For me, this is the litmus test of whether&nbsp;
our pronouncements and discussions actually&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:56.520 --> 00:08:02.640
correspond to something real. Ultimately, we&nbsp;
want to be able to illustrate what we're doing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:03.480 --> 00:08:13.500
so explicitly, so concretely, so precisely that a&nbsp;
computer can do it. This, of course, removes from&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:13.500 --> 00:08:21.540
consideration so much of modern 20th-century-style&nbsp;
infinite analyses. I think we have to let go of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:21.540 --> 00:08:27.360
that, people. We have to let go of that and move&nbsp;
into a much clearer, much more concise, and much&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:27.360 --> 00:08:34.200
more logical approach that is firmly and&nbsp;
always connected with computational reality.

00:08:35.700 --> 00:08:43.200
A big adventure is about to start for us, with&nbsp;
lots of opportunities for thinking outside the box&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:44.340 --> 00:08:50.400
with box arithmetic. I'm Norman&nbsp;
Wildberger. Thanks for listening.

